  :prose
"Fireworks, smoke, sparks, water, fire, dust, blood, snow, mist,
confetti, exhaust, magic sparkles, breath in cold air. All of these
are particle systems. All of them are the same idea underneath:
spawn many small entities, give each a lifetime and a few forces,
let them run.

The magic of particle systems is that they're the cheapest possible
visual effect that reads as physically real. A single particle is a
dot with a velocity, a color, and a countdown. Two hundred of them,
tuned right, look like water spray. Change gravity's sign and the
color and you have smoke rising. Change to short lifetime and hot
colors and you have sparks. The system's identity is entirely in the
tuning.

This chapter builds five particle systems that share 90% of their
code and 100% of their physics: sparks, fire, smoke, water, and
confetti.

---

## 9.1 One spark

```scheme
(define (spawn-spark x y)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'spark x y))
        (angle (* 2 3.14159 (random))))
    (entity/mass!          p 0.1)
    (entity/set-vel!       p (* 3 (cos angle)) (* 3 (sin angle)))
    (entity/gravity-scale! p 0.5)     ;; gravity affects sparks less
    (entity/drag!          p 0.03)    ;; air slows them
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life 60);; 60-frame lifetime
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'color-hot orange)
    p))
```

`ai/bb-set!` writes to the entity's little scratchpad. We use it for
lifetime and color. Each frame we decrement 'life; when it hits zero
we despawn.

```scheme
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (world/each 'spark
      (lambda (p)
        (let ((life (ai/bb-get p 'life)))
          (ai/bb-set! p 'life (- life 1))
          (when (<= (- life 1) 0)
            (entity/despawn! p))
          (let ((pos (entity/pos p)))
            (paint-circle (car pos) (cdr pos) 1
              (ai/bb-get p 'color-hot))))))))
```

Every 30 frames or so, spawn a spark burst:

```scheme
(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 30))
      (repeat 20 (lambda () (spawn-spark 240 180))))))
```

A twenty-spark burst every half-second. Watch the sparks fan out,
fall, fade, disappear.

## 9.2 Fire — the same pattern, tuned

Fire is sparks that fade from orange to red to black over their
lifetime, drift upward instead of falling, and are spawned
continuously from a source.

```scheme
(define (spawn-flame x y)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'flame
             (+ x (- (* 4 (random)) 2))
             y))
        (up-vel (- 0.5 (random))))
    (entity/mass!          p 0.05)
    (entity/set-vel!       p (- (* 0.6 (random)) 0.3) up-vel)
    (entity/gravity-scale! p -0.3)     ;; negative gravity: buoyancy
    (entity/drag!          p 0.04)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life 40)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life-max 40)
    p))

;; Age-dependent color: hot at start, cool at end.
(define (flame-color life-frac)
  (cond ((> life-frac 0.7) yellow)
        ((> life-frac 0.4) orange)
        ((> life-frac 0.1) red)
        (else              black)))

(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (repeat 3 (lambda () (spawn-flame 240 240)))
    (world/each 'flame
      (lambda (p)
        (let ((life (ai/bb-get p 'life))
              (life-max (ai/bb-get p 'life-max)))
          (ai/bb-set! p 'life (- life 1))
          (when (<= (- life 1) 0) (entity/despawn! p))
          (let ((pos (entity/pos p)))
            (paint-circle (car pos) (cdr pos) 3
              (flame-color (/ life life-max)))))))))
```

Three new flames per frame at (240, 240). They rise, drift, cool,
disappear. The color transition from yellow to black-red is what
sells the effect. It also composes: put three or five of these
emitters at different x-positions and it's a campfire; put one on
each corner of a rectangle and it's a burning building.

## 9.3 Smoke — like fire but grayer, slower, longer-lived

```scheme
(define (spawn-smoke x y)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'smoke x y))
        (life (+ 80 (random-int 40))))
    (entity/mass!          p 0.02)
    (entity/set-vel!       p (- (* 0.4 (random)) 0.2)
                             (- (* 0.3 (random)) 0.1))
    (entity/gravity-scale! p -0.2)
    (entity/drag!          p 0.06)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life life)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life-max life)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'size (+ 2 (* 4 (random))))
    p))
```

Longer life, slower rise, more drag, larger size that grows over time,
and gray colors that fade to transparent. Smoke.

## 9.4 Water — many particles + separation force + gravity

Water is more particles, gravity pulling down, and short-range
separation so they don't overlap. Real fluid sim (SPH) is next
chapter; this is the fake-fluid particle version.

```scheme
(define (spawn-drop x y)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'drop x y)))
    (entity/mass!    p 0.3)
    (entity/set-vel! p (- (* 3 (random)) 1.5) 2)
    (entity/drag!    p 0.02)
    (ai/separate     p 'drop 6 1.2)     ;; short-range repulsion
    (ai/bb-set!      p 'life 200)
    p))

(world/gravity! 0 0.4)
(world/floor!   380)                    ;; puddle at y=380

(on-frame
  (lambda (t)
    (world/step)
    (when (= 0 (modulo t 4))
      (spawn-drop 240 40))
    (world/each 'drop
      (lambda (p)
        (let ((pos (entity/pos p)))
          (paint-circle (car pos) (cdr pos) 2 blue))))))
```

Drops fall from a tap, splash on the puddle, spread out on the
'floor.' The separation keeps them from stacking into a single point.
It looks like water because it BEHAVES like water — falls, splashes,
piles.

## 9.5 Confetti — small quads, gravity, no repulsion, rotating

Confetti is not spherical, so it rotates. Give each particle a
random angular velocity.

```scheme
(define (spawn-confetti x y)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'confetti x y)))
    (entity/mass!          p 0.05)
    (entity/set-vel!       p (- (* 8 (random)) 4) (- (* 4 (random)) 2))
    (entity/gravity-scale! p 1.0)
    (entity/drag!          p 0.05)
    (entity/angular-vel!   p (- (* 12 (random)) 6))
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'life 180)
    (ai/bb-set!            p 'color (random-color))
    p))
```

Then paint each confetto as a rotated rectangle:

```scheme
(world/each 'confetti
  (lambda (p)
    (let ((pos (entity/pos p))
          (a   (entity/angle p))
          (c   (ai/bb-get p 'color)))
      (paint-rect-rotated (car pos) (cdr pos) 4 8 a c))))
```

Two hundred confetti drop from the top on a click. Watch them tumble.

## 9.6 A general particle-system record

You can capture the pattern in a record and re-use it.

```scheme
(define spark-preset
  '((tag . spark)
    (count-per-burst . 20)
    (life . (40 . 80))
    (vel . (radial 2 4))
    (gravity-scale . 0.5)
    (drag . 0.03)
    (color . (fade orange red black))
    (paint . dot)
    (size . 1)))

(define fire-preset
  '((tag . flame)
    (rate . 3)
    (life . (30 . 50))
    (vel . ((random -0.3 0.3) (random -0.5 0)))
    (gravity-scale . -0.3)
    (drag . 0.04)
    (color . (age yellow orange red black))
    (paint . dot)
    (size . 3)))

(particle-emitter spark-preset 240 180 :on 'click)
(particle-emitter fire-preset  400 240 :on 'always)
```

`particle-emitter` reads the preset and installs an emitter at the
given position. All the boilerplate above (spawn, tune, life-count,
color, paint) is expressed as data. Now you have a system that lets
you build particle effects without writing new code — just tweak the
preset.

---

## 9.7 The four routing patterns in particle systems

**Composition.** Each preset is a composition of tuning parameters.
Each particle's per-frame behavior is a composition of update-life,
update-vel, update-pos, paint. `particle-emitter` composes 'read
preset,' 'spawn N per frame,' 'wire per-particle updates.'

**Orchestration.** A firework sequence is orchestration in time:
launch shell (rocket rising) → detonate (spark burst) → fade (short
sparks + long smoke trail). A campfire that grows into a bonfire is
an orchestration that increases spawn rate over time.

**In-routing.** Click events route to a burst spawner. Physics
collisions (a spark hits a wall) route to a bounce handler or a
despawn. When a particle's life reaches zero, that event routes to
despawn — an internal in-router.

**Routing.** Particles route to the framebuffer as circles, dots, or
rotated quads. Audio ('spark hit') routes to `audio/play`. Particle
metrics ('300 active particles') route to a performance overlay.

---

## 9.8 Common desktop tasks

An operator running an online candy shop asked: 'when a customer
finishes a purchase, can we do a celebration animation?' A one-line
`(particle-emitter confetti-preset middle-of-screen :on 'purchase)`
gives them a two-second confetti burst that reads as celebration.
Cheap, fast, universally understood.

## 9.9 Try this

1. Make a rain preset. Which parameters differ from water?
2. Make an explosion preset. Radial vel, short life, orange to black,
   plus a shockwave (single expanding ring, not a particle).
3. Chain: spawn a rocket. When it explodes, spawn a burst of sparks.
   Each spark, on despawn, spawns a smaller burst of dust.
4. Draw with your mouse: each frame, spawn a particle at the mouse
   position with velocity in the mouse-motion direction. You've made
   a particle brush.
5. Make a preset that looks like snow. Gravity low, drag high, size
   ~2, color white, life long.

## 9.10 Pitfalls

**Too many particles.** Each particle is O(1) but there are many.
2000 particles at 60fps is fine on modern hardware; 20000 is not.
Cap with `particle-cap`.

**Never despawning.** If you forget the life countdown, particles
accumulate forever. Watch performance decay.

**Uniform is boring.** Random per-particle parameters (velocity,
life, color hue) look much more natural than perfectly-identical
particles.

